[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:compose-multiplatform/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:compose-multiplatform/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] In Compose, a user interface is defined using functions that have been annotated with the `@Composable` annotation, which are known as composable functions and define the screen's state.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Jetpack Compose uses a Kotlin compiler plugin to transform composable functions into UI elements.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] The first preview of Jetpack Compose was announced at the Google I/O conference in May 2019.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] The developer preview was released in October 2019, and the alpha release occurred in August 2020.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Compose entered its beta phase in February 2021, with its first production release taking place that July.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Jetpack Compose supports Android 5.0 and later.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] It uses the Kotlin programming language, and provides a reactive programming model similar to other UI frameworks such as Flutter, Vue.js, and React Native.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Compose is designed to integrate seamlessly with existing Android apps and libraries, allowing developers to gradually migrate their apps to Compose.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] The annotation is used by the Compose compiler to generate the UI boilerplate code.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] When the state is updated, composable functions are called again with new data, which causes the widgets they emit to be redrawn in a process known as recomposition.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Recomposition is only performed for composable functions that need to be updated, which improves UI efficiency.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] The 1.0 release introduced Compose Preview, which is built into Android Studio starting with Arctic Fox.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] It allows composables to be previewed using different configurations without deploying the app to a device.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Jetpack Glance is a Jetpack Compose-based framework for developing widgets for Android.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Glance's first stable release occurred in September 2023.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] In September 2024, the 1.0 stable version of the Jetpack Compose application programming interfaces (APIs) for building adaptive UIs with Material 3 was released.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] When Jetpack Compose 1.0 was released, Google said, "There are already over 2,000 apps in the Play Store using Compose – in fact, the Play Store app itself uses Compose." As of October 2022, 16% of the top 1000 apps on the Play Store included Compose.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] The apps included those from companies such as Airbnb, Lyft, and Square.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] In May 2024, this number had grown to 40%.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] In 2022, Google detailed how it utilized Jetpack Compose as part of its rewrite of the Play Store app, stating that "writing UI requires much less code, sometimes up to 50%" and that the developers were able to improve the app's performance.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Google rewrote parts of Android's Settings app using Jetpack Compose in Android 14.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] Meta Platforms developed its Threads social media app in five months using Jetpack Compose.
[src:compose-multiplatform/jetpack-compose] The Instagram for Android app has also been written using Jetpack Compose.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced Kotlin had become its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Since the release of Android Studio 3.0 in October 2017, Kotlin has been included as an alternative to the standard Java compiler.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin has support for the web with Kotlin/JS, through an intermediate representation-based backend that has been declared stable since version 1.8, released in December 2022.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin/Native (e.g., Apple silicon support) has been declared stable since version 1.9.20, released in November 2023.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] The name is derived from Kotlin Island, a Russian island in the Gulf of Finland, near Saint Petersburg.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Andrey Breslav, Kotlin's former lead designer, mentioned that the team decided to name it after an island, in imitation of the Java programming language, which shares a name with the Indonesian island of Java.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] The first commit to the Kotlin Git repository was on 8 November 2010.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] In July 2011, JetBrains unveiled Project Kotlin, a new JVM language that had been under development for a year.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains lead Dmitry Jemerov said that most languages lacked the features they were looking for, except for Scala.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] However, he cited Scala's slow compilation time as a deficiency.
