[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Semicolons are optional as a statement terminator; in most cases, a newline is sufficient for the compiler to deduce that the statement has ended.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin variable declarations and parameter lists place the data type after the variable name (separated by a colon), similar to Ada, BASIC, Pascal, TypeScript, and Rust.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.3 added support for contracts, which are stable for the standard library declarations, but still experimental for user-defined declarations.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Contracts are inspired by the design-by-contract programming paradigm.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Like Scala.js, Kotlin code can be transpiled to JavaScript, enabling interoperability between Kotlin and JavaScript and allowing either writing complete web applications in Kotlin or sharing code between a Kotlin backend and a JavaScript frontend.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin relaxes the Java restriction on static methods and variables, allowing them to exist outside a class body.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Static objects and functions can be defined at the top level of the package without requiring a redundant class-level scope.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] For compatibility with Java, Kotlin provides the `JvmName` annotation, which specifies the class name used when the package is viewed from a Java project.
