[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] As in C, C++, C#, Java, and Go, the entry point to a Kotlin program is a function named `main`, which may be passed an array containing any command-line arguments.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Perl, PHP, and Unix shell–style string interpolation is supported.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin provides the following keywords to restrict visibility for top-level declarations (such as classes) and for class members: `public`, `internal`, `protected`, and `private`.
[src:compose-multiplatform/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin distinguishes between nullable and non-nullable data types.
