[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:compose-multiplatform/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] The **Skia Graphics Engine** or **Skia** is an open-source 2D graphics library written in C++.
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia abstracts away platform-specific graphics APIs (which differ from one to another).
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia Inc. originally developed the library; Google acquired it in 2005, and then released the software as open source licensed under the New BSD free software license in 2008.
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] In order to stay multi-platform, Skia supports several (platform-dependent) back-ends.
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia is most similar in purpose to Cairo or Pathfinder (meaning that it focuses on drawing) rather than to other more elaborate APIs like that of Qt that provide their own widgets and UI description language etc.
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] The library is used as of 2023 in Google Chrome, ChromeOS, ChromiumOS, Mozilla Firefox, Mozilla Thunderbird, Android, Firefox OS, Flutter, Ladybird, Avalonia (from Alpha 4), LibreOffice (from version 7.0) and RAD Studio(since version 12.0).
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia is a romanisation of the word 'shadow' in Greek (Σκιά).
[src:compose-multiplatform/skia-graphics-engine] Skia Inc, developers of the Skia Graphics Engine, was founded in 2004 by Mike Reed and Cary Clark in Chapel Hill North Carolina, before being acquired by Google in 2005.
